05436nam a22007455i 9780824837877DE-B159720210824034702.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210824t20132013hiu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808248378777 a10.1515/97808248378772doi  a(DE-B1597)484447  a(OCoLC)855697753  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  ahiucUS-HI 7aSOC0020102bisacsh04a305.42095982231 aSaraswati, L. Ayu, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aSeeing Beauty, Sensing Race in Transnational Indonesia /cL. Ayu Saraswati; ed. by Rita Smith Kipp, David P. Chandler. 1aHonolulu : bUniversity of Hawaii Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aSoutheast Asia: Politics, Meaning, and Memory ;v5100tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction. Seeing Beauty, Sensing Race in Transnational Indonesia -- tCHAPTER 1. Rasa, Race, and Ramayana: Sensing and Censoring the History of Color in Precolonial Java -- tCHAPTER 2. Rooting and Routing Whiteness in Colonial Indonesia: From Dutch to Japanese Whiteness -- tCHAPTER 3. Indonesian White Beauty: Spatializing Race and Racializing Spatial Tropes -- tCHAPTER 4. Cosmopolitan Whiteness: The Effects and Affects of Skin- Whitening Advertisements in a Transnational Women’s Magazine -- tCHAPTER 5. Malu: Coloring Shame and Shaming the Color of Beauty -- tConclusion. Shades of Emotions in a Transnational Context -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex -- tAbout the Author -- tOther Volumes in the Series0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn Indonesia, light skin color has been desirable throughout recorded history. Seeing Beauty, Sensing Race explores Indonesia’s changing beauty ideals and traces them to a number of influences: first to ninth-century India and some of the oldest surviving Indonesian literary works; then, a thousand years later, to the impact of Dutch colonialism and the wartime occupation of Japan; and finally, in the post-colonial period, to the popularity of American culture. The book shows how the transnational circulation of people, images, and ideas have shaped and shifted discourses and hierarchies of race, gender, skin color, and beauty in Indonesia. The author employs “affect” theories and feminist cultural studies as a lens through which to analyze a vast range of materials, including the Old Javanese epic poem Ramayana, archival materials, magazine advertisements, commercial products, and numerous interviews with Indonesian women.The book offers a rich repertoire of analytical and theoretical tools that allow readers to rethink issues of race and gender in a global context and understand how feelings and emotions—Western constructs as well as Indian, Javanese, and Indonesian notions such as rasa and malu—contribute to and are constitutive of transnational and gendered processes of racialization. Saraswati argues that it is how emotions come to be attached to certain objects and how they circulate that shape the “emotionscape” of white beauty in Indonesia. Her ground-breaking work is a nuanced theoretical exploration of the ways in which representations of beauty and the emotions they embody travel geographically and help shape attitudes and beliefs toward race and gender in a transnational world.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Aug 2021) 0aFeminine beauty (Aesthetics)zIndonesia. 0aHuman skin colorzIndonesiaxPsychological aspects. 0aRace awarenesszIndonesia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Anthropology / Cultural & Social.2bisacsh1 aChandler, David P., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aKipp, Rita Smith, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies B